Q: What is data preprocessing?
   [Asked in: P8-1a]

Data preprocessing is the essential first step in any machine learning pipeline. It
involves cleaning, transforming, and organizing raw data into a structured format
that machine learning algorithms can effectively learn from.

Raw data collected from real-world sources typically contains numerous issues:
  - Missing values (blank cells, NaN, null entries)
  - Outliers (extreme values that distort the model)
  - Inconsistent formats (dates in different formats, mixed units)
  - Duplicate records
  - Wrong data types (numbers stored as text, categories stored as numbers)
  - Imbalanced feature scales (age: 20-60 vs. salary: 20000-200000)
  - Categorical variables that need to be converted to numbers

Key Steps in Data Preprocessing:
  1. Data Cleaning: Handle missing values (imputation or deletion), remove duplicates,
     fix inconsistent entries, and correct wrong data types.
  2. Outlier Detection and Treatment: Identify outliers using box plots, IQR method,
     or Z-scores. Treat them by capping, flooring, removing, or transforming.
  3. Feature Encoding: Convert categorical variables to numerical format using
     techniques like Label Encoding, One-Hot Encoding, Target Encoding, or
     Frequency Encoding.
  4. Feature Scaling: Standardize or normalize numerical features to bring them
     to a comparable range (Z-score standardization, Min-Max scaling).
  5. Feature Selection: Select only the most relevant features and remove redundant
     or irrelevant ones using correlation analysis, VIF, forward/backward selection.
  6. Data Splitting: Divide the preprocessed data into training and testing sets
     (commonly 70:30 or 80:20 ratio) to evaluate model generalization.

Why It Matters:
  - Garbage in, garbage out: A model trained on dirty data will produce unreliable
    predictions, no matter how sophisticated the algorithm is.
  - Proper preprocessing can significantly improve model accuracy, stability, and
    interpretability.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q: Explain any two of the data preprocessing steps.
   [Asked in: P1-1e]

Data preprocessing is the process of transforming raw data into a clean, usable format
before feeding it into a machine learning model. Two important preprocessing steps:

  1. Handling Missing Values
     Real-world datasets frequently have missing entries due to data collection errors,
     sensor failures, survey non-responses, or system glitches.

     Strategies to handle missing data:
     a) Deletion:
        - Listwise deletion: Remove entire rows containing any missing value. This is
          simple but can lead to significant data loss if many rows have missing values.
        - Column deletion: Drop an entire column/feature if it has a very high
          percentage of missing values (e.g., more than 40-50%).
     b) Imputation:
        - Mean/Median imputation: Replace missing numerical values with the mean (for
          normally distributed data) or median (for skewed data) of that column.
        - Mode imputation: Replace missing categorical values with the most frequent
          category.
        - KNN Imputer: Use K-Nearest Neighbors to predict the missing value based on
          the values of similar data points.
        - Forward/Backward fill: For time-series data, fill missing values using the
          previous (forward fill) or next (backward fill) available value.

  2. Feature Scaling (Normalization / Standardization)
     Machine learning algorithms that use distance metrics (like KNN, K-Means, SVM) or
     gradient-based optimization (like linear regression via gradient descent) are
     sensitive to the scale of input features. If one feature ranges from 0-1 and
     another from 0-100000, the larger-scale feature will dominate.

     Techniques:
     a) Standardization (Z-score normalization):
        Transforms each feature to have mean = 0 and standard deviation = 1.
        Formula: x_scaled = (x - mean) / standard_deviation
        This is preferred when the data has outliers, since it does not bound the
        values to a specific range.
     b) Min-Max Scaling (Normalization):
        Transforms each feature to a fixed range, usually [0, 1].
        Formula: x_scaled = (x - x_min) / (x_max - x_min)
        This is preferred when we need bounded values, but it is sensitive to outliers.


