Q: Explain target encoding.
   [Asked in: P8-1b]

Target Encoding (also called Mean Encoding) is a technique for converting categorical
variables into numerical values by replacing each category with a statistic computed
from the target variable.

Procedure:
  1. For each unique category in a categorical feature, calculate the mean (or median)
     of the target variable for all observations belonging to that category.
  2. Replace every occurrence of that category with its computed mean target value.

Example:
  Suppose we have a "City" column and a target variable "Profit":

    City          Profit
    New York      500000
    New York      600000
    Mumbai        300000
    Mumbai        400000
    London        450000
    London        550000

  Target encoding for "City":
    New York -> mean(500000, 600000) = 550000
    Mumbai   -> mean(300000, 400000) = 350000
    London   -> mean(450000, 550000) = 500000

  After encoding:
    City_encoded  Profit
    550000        500000
    550000        600000
    350000        300000
    350000        400000
    500000        450000
    500000        550000

Advantages:
  - Does not increase dimensionality (unlike One-Hot Encoding, which creates many
    new columns for high-cardinality features).
  - Captures the relationship between the category and the target.
  - Works well with high-cardinality categorical features (e.g., city names, zip codes).

Risks and Mitigation:
  - Target Leakage: The encoding uses target variable information, which can lead to
    overfitting because the model "sees" the target during feature engineering.
  - Overfitting on Rare Categories: Categories with very few observations will have
    unreliable mean estimates.
  - Mitigation Strategies:
    a) Smoothing: Blend the category mean with the global target mean, weighted by
       the number of observations in that category. Categories with few observations
       get pulled toward the global mean.
    b) K-Fold Target Encoding: For each fold, compute the target mean using only the
       out-of-fold data to prevent leakage.
    c) Adding noise: Add small random noise to the encoded values to reduce overfitting.


