Q: State / Explain the assumptions of linear regression algorithm.
   [Asked in: P1-1c, P2-1c, P3-1c, P4-1b, P5-1a -- MOST REPEATED QUESTION]

Linear regression relies on several key assumptions. Violating these assumptions can
lead to biased, inefficient, or misleading coefficient estimates and predictions.

  1. Linearity
     The relationship between the independent variables (X) and the dependent variable
     (Y) is linear. That is, Y changes at a constant rate as X changes. This can be
     checked by plotting residuals vs. fitted values -- the plot should show no clear
     pattern (no curves or systematic shapes).

  2. Homoscedasticity (Constant Variance of Errors)
     The variance of the residuals (error terms) should remain constant across all
     levels of the independent variables. If the spread of residuals increases or
     decreases with the fitted values, the condition called heteroscedasticity exists.
     This can be checked using a residuals vs. fitted values plot or statistical tests
     like the Breusch-Pagan test or White's test.

  3. Independence of Errors (No Autocorrelation)
     The residuals should be independent of each other. There should be no systematic
     pattern in the residuals (i.e., one residual should not predict the next).
     This is especially important in time-series data. It can be tested using the
     Durbin-Watson test (values near 2 indicate no autocorrelation).

  4. Normality of Residuals
     The residuals should follow a normal (Gaussian) distribution. This assumption is
     important for hypothesis testing (t-tests, F-tests) and confidence intervals.
     It can be checked using a Q-Q (quantile-quantile) plot, histogram of residuals,
     or statistical tests like the Shapiro-Wilk test or Kolmogorov-Smirnov test.

  5. No or Low Multicollinearity
     The independent variables should not be highly correlated with each other. High
     multicollinearity inflates the standard errors of coefficients, making them
     unreliable and unstable. It can be detected using a correlation matrix (pairwise
     r > 0.8 is concerning) or by computing the Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) for
     each feature (VIF > 5 or 10 indicates a problem).

  6. No Endogeneity (Exogeneity of Regressors)
     The error terms should have a mean of zero and should not be correlated with the
     independent variables. If an independent variable is correlated with the error
     term, the coefficient estimate for that variable will be biased.


