Q: Explain Forward Selection in brief.
   [Asked in: P2-2a, P3-1d, P6-1d, P7-1d]

Forward Selection is a stepwise, iterative, wrapper-based feature selection method that
builds a model by adding one feature at a time, starting from an empty model.

Procedure:
  Step 1: Start with a null model containing no independent variables (only the
          intercept/constant term).
  Step 2: Fit a separate simple linear regression model for each available feature
          individually. Evaluate each model's performance using a criterion such as
          p-value, AIC (Akaike Information Criterion), BIC (Bayesian Information
          Criterion), or Adjusted R^2.
  Step 3: Select the single feature that gives the best performance (e.g., lowest
          p-value or lowest AIC) and add it to the model permanently.
  Step 4: With the selected feature already in the model, fit new models by adding
          each of the remaining features one at a time. Again, evaluate performance.
  Step 5: If the best new feature provides a statistically significant improvement
          (e.g., its p-value is below the threshold alpha = 0.05), add it to the model.
  Step 6: Repeat Steps 4-5 until no remaining feature provides a significant
          improvement, or all features have been added.

Advantages: Computationally less expensive than exhaustive search; straightforward
            to implement and interpret.
Disadvantages: May miss the optimal subset because it never reconsiders features
               already added; it is a greedy algorithm.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q: Write a note on Backward elimination method of feature selection algorithms.
   [Asked in: P4-1d]

Backward Elimination is a stepwise, iterative, wrapper-based feature selection method
that starts with all candidate features and progressively removes the least significant
ones.

Procedure:
  Step 1: Start with a full model containing all available independent variables.

  Step 2: Fit the model (e.g., using OLS regression) and generate the summary report
          with p-values for each coefficient.

  Step 3: Identify the feature with the highest p-value.

  Step 4: If this highest p-value is greater than the chosen significance level
          (alpha, typically 0.05):
          - Remove that feature from the model.
          - Go back to Step 2 and re-fit the model with the remaining features.

  Step 5: If the highest p-value is less than or equal to alpha:
          - Stop. All remaining features are statistically significant at the chosen
            alpha level. The current model is the final model.

Advantages:
  - Simple to implement and understand.
  - Considers the effect of each variable in the presence of all other variables.
  - Tends to produce more stable results than forward selection because it starts
    with the full picture.

Disadvantages:
  - Computationally expensive for datasets with a very large number of features,
    since it begins by fitting a model with all variables.
  - A greedy algorithm -- it may not find the globally optimal subset of features.
  - Once a variable is removed, it is never reconsidered.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q: Write steps for Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE).
   [Asked in: P8-1d]

Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE) is a backward-selection wrapper method that
identifies the most important features by iteratively building models and removing
the weakest feature(s) at each step.

Detailed Steps:

  Step 1: Start with all available features in the dataset.

  Step 2: Train a model that provides feature importance scores or coefficient values.
          Common estimators used with RFE include:
          - Linear Regression (uses absolute coefficient values)
          - Logistic Regression (uses absolute coefficient values)
          - Random Forest (uses feature importance based on impurity reduction)
          - Gradient Boosting (uses feature importance)

  Step 3: Rank all features based on their importance/coefficient values from the
          trained model.

  Step 4: Remove the feature with the lowest importance (or the bottom n features
          if eliminating in batches for speed).

  Step 5: Re-train the model on the reduced feature set.

  Step 6: Repeat Steps 3-5 until the desired number of features is reached, or until
          a stopping criterion is met (e.g., cross-validation score stops improving).

  Step 7: The remaining features are the selected "best" features.

In Python (sklearn):
  from sklearn.feature_selection import RFE
  from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

  model = LinearRegression()
  rfe = RFE(estimator=model, n_features_to_select=5)
  rfe.fit(X_train, y_train)
  selected_features = X_train.columns[rfe.support_]

Variant -- RFECV:
  RFE with Cross-Validation (RFECV) automatically determines the optimal number of
  features by evaluating the cross-validation score at each step. It selects the
  number of features that gives the best CV performance.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMPARISON: Forward Selection vs Backward Elimination vs RFE
(Added for exam reference)

  Feature             Forward Selection     Backward Elimination   RFE
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Starting point      Empty model           Full model             Full model
  Direction           Adds features         Removes features       Removes features
  Criterion           p-value / AIC / R^2   p-value                Model importance
  Feature selection?  Yes (implicitly)      Yes (implicitly)       Yes (explicitly)
  Re-evaluates?       No (greedy)           No (greedy)            Yes (re-trains)
  Uses model weights? No (uses p-values)    No (uses p-values)     Yes (uses coefs)
  sklearn support?    Custom code needed    Custom code needed     sklearn.RFE


